<BaseLayout title="About" description="Smartcashflow explains personal finance with calm tools and no sales pressure."><section class="hero-dark"><div class="container container--narrow" style="position:relative;padding-block:clamp(56px,8vw,104px);text-align:center"><div class="eyebrow eyebrow--cream no-rule" style="justify-content:center;margin-bottom:18px">Our purpose</div><h1 class="display" style="color:var(--paper);font-size:clamp(2.2rem,5vw,3.6rem)">Money advice that earns your <span class="serif-italic" style="color:var(--brass-300)">trust</span>.</h1><p class="lede" style="color:rgba(244,240,230,.8);margin:20px auto 0;max-width:54ch">Smartcashflow exists to give households clear, unbiased guidance on decisions that move the needle — without jargon, fear, or sales pressure.</p></div></section><section class="section--tight container container--narrow"><div class="prose-article"><p>Most financial content is written to sell something. Smartcashflow keeps the scope deliberately narrow: personal finance, emergency funds, insurance, cash flow, and retirement.</p><p>Every article pairs with a practical next step, and every calculator runs entirely in your browser. We never see your inputs.</p><blockquote>We would rather publish one guide that changes how you think than ten that fill a calendar.</blockquote></div></section><section class="section--tight container"><div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:12px">What we stand for</div><h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:28px">Principles we do not bend</h2><div class="cards-2"><div class="card" style="padding:24px"><h3>Accuracy first</h3><p class="muted">We cite primary sources and update stale assumptions.</p></div><div class="card" style="padding:24px"><h3>No conflicts</h3><p class="muted">We do not sell insurance, funds, or leads.</p></div><div class="card" style="padding:24px"><h3>Plain language</h3><p class="muted">If a sentence needs a glossary, it gets rewritten.</p></div><div class="card" style="padding:24px"><h3>For real life</h3><p class="muted">Advice should survive tight months and irregular income.</p></div></div></section></BaseLayout>
